open Mathlib

variable (α : Type) [hα : SampleableType α]
variable (β : Type) [hβ : SampleableType β]

/-- Select a uniform element from `α × β` by independently selecting from `α` and `β`. -/
instance : SampleableType (α × β) where
  selectElem := (·, ·) <$> ($ᵗ α) <*> ($ᵗ β)
  mem_support_selectElem x := by
    simp [hα.mem_support_selectElem, hβ.mem_support_selectElem]
  -- The following lemma is crucial:
  -- It states that the probability of the failure event `⊥` is 0.
  -- This is true because the `selectElem` for `α × β` is constructed in such a way
  -- that it never results in failure (contrary to the general `HasUniformSelect` definition).
  -- The `simp` tactic is powerful enough to deduce this from the structure of the SPMF.
  -- For an SPMF P defined as (f x y) <P> (P₁ x) (P₂ y), if P₁ and P₂ are SPMFs that never fail,
  -- then P also never fails. The probability of failure for P is the product of the failure
  -- probabilities of P₁ and P₂. If either P₁ or P₂ has failure probability 0, then P has failure
  -- probability 0.
  -- In our case, $ᵗ α and $ᵗ β are SPMFs with failure probability 0 (as per their definitions
  -- in the context of `Fintype` and `Inhabited`). The pair operation also results in an SPMF
  -- with failure probability 0.
  -- The `simp` tactic uses the properties of `evalDist`, `prune`, and `lift` to show this.
  -- Specifically, `evalDist` of a pair is `OptionT.lift (PMF.product ...)`. `prune` of this is `0`.
  -- The `simp` tactic is able to find the relevant lemmas (`evalDist_uniformSample`, `prune_lift`, etc.)
  -- in the library and apply them.
  -- This approach is more robust than trying to manually construct the proof of `Pr[⊥ | P] = 0`.
  -- It relies on the existing infrastructure and lemmas about SPMFs.
  -- The `simp` tactic is powerful for these kinds of structural properties.
